[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] In probability theory, the **conditional expectation**, **conditional expected value**, or **conditional mean** of a random variable is its expected value evaluated with respect to the conditional probability distribution.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] If the random variable can take on only a finite number of values, the "conditions" are that the variable can only take on a subset of those values.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] More formally, in the case when the random variable is defined over a discrete probability space, the "conditions" are a partition of this probability space.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] Depending on the context, the conditional expectation can be either a random variable or a function.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] The random variable is denoted $E(X\mid Y)$ analogously to conditional probability.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] The function form is either denoted $E(X\mid Y=y)$ or a separate function symbol such as $f(y)$ is introduced with the meaning $E(X\mid Y)=f(Y)$ .
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] Consider the roll of a fair dice and let *A* = 1 if the number is even (i.e., 2, 4, or 6) and *A* = 0 otherwise.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] Furthermore, let *B* = 1 if the number is prime (i.e., 2, 3, or 5) and *B* = 0 otherwise.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] Suppose we have daily rainfall data (mm of rain each day) collected by a weather station on every day of the ten-year (3652-day) period from January 1, 1990, to December 31, 1999.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] The unconditional expectation of rainfall for an unspecified day is the average of the rainfall amounts for those 3652 days.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] The *conditional* expectation of rainfall for an otherwise unspecified day known to be (conditional on being) in the month of March, is the average of daily rainfall over all 310 days of the ten–year period that fall in March.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] Similarly, the conditional expectation of rainfall conditional on days dated March 2 is the average of the rainfall amounts that occurred on the ten days with that specific date.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] The related concept of conditional probability dates back at least to Laplace, who calculated conditional distributions.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] It was Andrey Kolmogorov who, in 1933, formalized it using the Radon–Nikodym theorem.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] Doob from 1953, conditional expectation was generalized to its modern definition using sub-*σ*-algebras.
