[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] Conditioning on a continuous random variable is not the same as conditioning on the event $\{Y=y\}$ as it was in the discrete case.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] For a discussion, see Conditioning on an event of probability zero.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] Not respecting this distinction can lead to contradictory conclusions as illustrated by the Borel-Kolmogorov paradox.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] All random variables in this section are assumed to be in $L^{2}$ , that is square integrable.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] In its full generality, conditional expectation is developed without this assumption, see below under Conditional expectation with respect to a sub-*σ*-algebra.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] The $L^{2}$ theory is, however, considered more intuitive and admits important generalizations.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] In the context of $L^{2}$ random variables, conditional expectation is also called regression.
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] In what follows let $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},P)$ be a probability space, and $X:\Omega \to \mathbb {R}$ in $L^{2}$ with mean $\mu _{X}$ and variance $\sigma _{X}^{2}$ .
[src:martingale-theory/conditional-expectation] The conditional expectation of X is defined analogously, except instead of a single number $\mu _{X}$ , the result will be a function $e_{X}(y)$ .
