[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] In mathematics, **Doob's martingale inequality**, also known as **Kolmogorov's submartingale inequality**, is a fundamental result in the study of stochastic processes.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] The setting of Doob's inequality is a submartingale relative to a filtration of the underlying probability space.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] Informally, Doob's inequality states that the expected value of the process at some final time controls the probability that a sample path will reach above any particular value beforehand.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] As the proof uses very direct reasoning, it does not require any restrictive assumptions on the underlying filtration or on the process itself, unlike for many other theorems about stochastic processes.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] In the continuous-time setting, right-continuity (or left-continuity) of the sample paths is required, but only for the sake of knowing that the supremal value of a sample path equals the supremum over an arbitrary countable dense subset of times.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] In this proof, the submartingale property is used once, together with the definition of conditional expectation.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] The proof can also be phrased in the language of stochastic processes so as to become a corollary of the powerful theorem that a stopped submartingale is itself a submartingale.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] In this setup, the minimal index i appearing in the above proof is interpreted as a stopping time.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] This passage from discrete time to continuous time is very flexible, as it only requires having a countable dense subset of $[0,T]$ , which can then automatically be built out of an increasing sequence of finite sets.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] As such, the submartingale inequality holds even for more general index sets, which are not required to be intervals or natural numbers.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] There are further submartingale inequalities also due to Doob.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] Now let $X_{t}$ be a martingale or a positive submartingale; if the index set is uncountable, then (as above) assume that the sample paths are right-continuous.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] Here T is the *final time*, i.e. the largest value of the index set.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] which is precisely the statement of Kolmogorov's inequality.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] Doob's maximal inequality, particularly in the $p=2$ case, is foundational to the rigorous construction of the Itô integral.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] It guarantees that the sequence of integrals of simple predictable processes converges uniformly in the space of square-integrable martingales.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] This boundedness is what allows the integral definition to be safely extended to a much broader class of predictable processes via the Itô isometry.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] The submartingale inequality serves as a fundamental stepping stone in the proofs of Doob's martingale convergence theorems.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] By bounding the probability of extreme excursions of the sample paths, it ensures that martingales with bounded expectations do not oscillate infinitely.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] This mathematically enforces the condition required for the sequence to converge almost surely to a well-defined limit.
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] Doob's inequality provides a direct way to bound the maximum of canonical one-dimensional Brownian motion, denoted here as B .
[src:martingale-theory/doob-s-martingale-inequality] Since the left-hand side does not depend on $\lambda$ , we can minimize the right-hand side by choosing $\lambda =C/T$ .
[src:martingale-theory/filtration-probability-theory] Let $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {A}},P)$ be a probability space and let I be an index set with a total order $\leq$ (often $\mathbb {N}$ , $\mathbb {R} ^{+}$ , or a subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{+}$ ).
[src:martingale-theory/filtration-probability-theory] is called a filtration, if ${\mathcal {F}}_{k}\subseteq {\mathcal {F}}_{\ell }$ for all $k\leq \ell$ .
[src:martingale-theory/filtration-probability-theory] So filtrations are families of *σ*-algebras that are ordered non-decreasingly.
[src:martingale-theory/filtration-probability-theory] If $\mathbb {F}$ is a filtration, then $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {A}},\mathbb {F} ,P)$ is called a **filtered probability space**.
[src:martingale-theory/filtration-probability-theory] Let $(X_{n})_{n\in \mathbb {N} }$ be a stochastic process on the probability space $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {A}},P)$ .
[src:martingale-theory/filtration-probability-theory] Let $\sigma (X_{k}\mid k\leq n)$ denote the *σ*-algebra generated by the random variables $X_{1},X_{2},\dots ,X_{n}$ .
[src:martingale-theory/filtration-probability-theory] This is known as the natural filtration of ${\mathcal {A}}$ with respect to $(X_{n})_{n\in \mathbb {N} }$ .
[src:martingale-theory/filtration-probability-theory] The filtration $\mathbb {F}$ itself is called right-continuous if $\mathbb {F} ^{+}=\mathbb {F}$ .
[src:martingale-theory/filtration-probability-theory] be the set of all sets that are contained within a P -null set.
[src:martingale-theory/filtration-probability-theory] A filtration is called an **augmented filtration** if it is complete and right continuous.
[src:martingale-theory/filtration-probability-theory] For every filtration $\mathbb {F}$ there exists a smallest augmented filtration ${\tilde {\mathbb {F} }}$ refining $\mathbb {F}$ .
[src:martingale-theory/filtration-probability-theory] If a filtration is an augmented filtration, it is said to satisfy the **usual hypotheses** or the **usual conditions**.
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] In probability theory, a **martingale** is a stochastic process in which the expected value of the next observation, given all prior observations, is equal to the most recent value.
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] In other words, the conditional expectation of the next value, given the past, is equal to the present value.
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] Martingales are used to model fair games, where future expected winnings are equal to the current amount regardless of past outcomes.
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] Originally, *martingale* referred to a class of betting strategies that was popular in 18th-century France.
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] That is, the conditional expected value of the next observation, given all the past observations, is equal to the most recent observation.
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] This expresses the property that the conditional expectation of an observation at time t , given all the observations up to time s , is equal to the observation at time s (provided that $s\leq t$ ).
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] The second property implies that $Y_{n}$ is measurable with respect to $X_{1},\dots ,X_{n}$ .
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] This is also called the martingale property.
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] The property of being a martingale involves both the filtration *and* the probability measure (with respect to which the expectations are taken).
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] It is possible that Y could be a martingale with respect to one measure but not another one; the Girsanov theorem offers a way to find a measure with respect to which an Itō process is a martingale.
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] In the Banach space setting the conditional expectation is also denoted in operator notation as $\mathbf {E} ^{\Sigma _{s}}Y_{t}$ .
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] with "+" in case of "heads" and "−" in case of "tails".
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] There are two generalizations of a martingale that include cases when the current observation $X_{n}$ is not necessarily equal to the future conditional expectation, but instead acts as an upper or lower bound on the conditional expectation.
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] A stopping time with respect to a sequence of random variables $X_{1},X_{2},X_{3},\dots$ is a random variable $\tau$ with the property that for each t , the occurrence or non-occurrence of the event $\tau =t$ depends only on the values of $X_{1},X_{2},\dots ,X_{t}$ .
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] The intuition behind the definition is that at any particular time t , you can look at the sequence so far and tell if it is time to stop.
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] An example might be the time at which a gambler leaves the gambling table, which might depend on previous winnings, but not on games that haven't been played yet.
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] In some contexts the concept of *stopping time* is defined by requiring only that the occurrence or non-occurrence of the event $\tau =t$ is probabilistically independent of $X_{t+1},X_{t+2},\dots$ but not completely determined by the history up to time t .
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] One of the basic properties of martingales is that, if $(X_{t})_{t>0}$ is a (sub-/super-) martingale and $\tau$ is a stopping time, then the corresponding stopped process $(X_{t}^{\tau })_{t>0}$ defined by $X_{t}^{\tau }:=X_{\min\{\tau ,t\}}$ is also a (sub-/super-) martingale.
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] The concept of a stopped martingale leads to a series of important theorems, including the optional stopping theorem which states that, under certain conditions, the expected value of a martingale at a stopping time is equal to its initial value.
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] The martingale problem is a framework in stochastic analysis for characterizing solutions to stochastic differential equations (SDEs) through martingale conditions.
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] Let E be a Polish space with Borel $\sigma$ -algebra ${\mathcal {E}}$ , and let ${\mathcal {P}}(E)$ be the set of probability measures on E .
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] Suppose $A:{\mathcal {D}}(A)\to C(E)$ is a Markov pregenerator, where ${\mathcal {D}}(A)$ is a dense subspace of $C(E)$ .
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] If $\mu =\delta _{\eta }$ (the Dirac measure at $\eta$ ), then $\mathbb {P}$ is said to solve the martingale problem for A with initial point $\eta$ .
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] Solutions to $M(a,b)$ correspond (in a weak sense) to solutions of the SDE $dX_{t}=b(X_{t})\,dt+\sigma (X_{t})\,dB_{t}$ , where $\sigma \sigma ^{\top }=a$ .
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] One sees this by applying the generator A to simple functions such as $x_{i}$ or $x_{i}x_{j}$ , thereby recovering the drift b and the diffusion matrix a .
[src:martingale-theory/martingale-probability-theory] Martingales form the foundational mathematics behind modern quantitative finance and asset pricing theory.
[src:martingale-theory/optional-stopping-theorem] In probability theory, the **optional stopping theorem** (or sometimes **Doob's optional sampling theorem**, for American probabilist Joseph Doob) says that, under certain conditions, the expected value of a martingale at a stopping time is equal to its initial expected value.
[src:martingale-theory/optional-stopping-theorem] A discrete-time version of the theorem is given below, with $\mathbb {N} _{0}$ denoting the set of natural numbers, including zero.
[src:martingale-theory/optional-stopping-theorem] Let $X=(X_{t})_{t\in \mathbb {N} _{0}}$ be a discrete-time martingale and $\tau$ a stopping time with values in $\mathbb {N} _{0}\cup \{\infty \}$ , both with respect to a filtration $({\mathcal {F}}_{t})_{t\in \mathbb {N} _{0}}$ .
[src:martingale-theory/optional-stopping-theorem] of the martingale increments are almost surely bounded.
[src:martingale-theory/optional-stopping-theorem] Then $X_{\tau }$ is an almost surely well-defined random variable and $\mathbb {E} [X_{\tau }]=\mathbb {E} [X_{0}]$ .
[src:martingale-theory/optional-stopping-theorem] Under condition (**c**) it is possible that $\tau =\infty$ happens with positive probability.
[src:martingale-theory/optional-stopping-theorem] On this event, $X_{\tau }$ is defined as the almost surely existing pointwise limit of $X=(X_{t})_{t\in \mathbb {N} _{0}}$ .
[src:martingale-theory/optional-stopping-theorem] Let $X^{\tau }$ denote the stopped process, which is also a martingale (or a submartingale or supermartingale, respectively).
[src:martingale-theory/optional-stopping-theorem] If condition (**c**) holds, then the stopped process $X^{\tau }$ is bounded by the constant random variable $M:=c$ .
[src:martingale-theory/optional-stopping-theorem] If condition (**a**) holds, then this series only has a finite number of non-zero terms, hence M is integrable.
[src:martingale-theory/optional-stopping-theorem] If condition (**b**) holds, then we continue by inserting a conditional expectation and using that the event $\{\tau >s\}$ is known at time s (note that $\tau$ is assumed to be a stopping time with respect to the filtration).
[src:martingale-theory/optional-stopping-theorem] Therefore, under any one of the three conditions in the theorem, the stopped process is dominated by an integrable random variable M .
[src:martingale-theory/optional-stopping-theorem] Similarly, if X is a submartingale or supermartingale, respectively, change the equality in the last two formulas to the appropriate inequality.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] A stopping time is often defined by a **stopping rule**, a mechanism for deciding whether to continue or stop a process on the basis of the present position and past events, and which will almost always lead to a decision to stop at some finite time.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Stopping times occur in decision theory, and the optional stopping theorem is an important result in this context.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Stopping times are also frequently applied in mathematical proofs to "tame the continuum of time", as Chung put it in his book (1982).
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Let $\tau$ be a random variable, which is defined on the filtered probability space $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},({\mathcal {F}}_{n})_{n\in \mathbb {N} },P)$ with values in $\mathbb {N} \cup \{+\infty \}$ .
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Intuitively, this condition means that the "decision" of whether to stop at time n must be based only on the information present at time n , not on any future information.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Let $\tau$ be a random variable, which is defined on the filtered probability space $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},({\mathcal {F}}_{t})_{t\in T},P)$ with values in T .
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Some authors explicitly exclude cases where $\tau$ can be $+\infty$ , whereas other authors allow $\tau$ to take any value in the closure of T .
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] To illustrate the more general definition of stopping time, consider Brownian motion, which is a stochastic process $(B_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ , where each $B_{t}$ is a random variable defined on the probability space $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},\mathbb {P} )$ .
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] We define a filtration on this probability space by letting ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ be the *σ*-algebra generated by all the sets of the form $(B_{s})^{-1}(A)$ where $0\leq s\leq t$ and $A\subseteq \mathbb {R}$ is a Borel set.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Intuitively, an event *E* is in ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ if and only if we can determine whether *E* is true or false just by observing the Brownian motion from time 0 to time *t*.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Hitting times like the second example above can be important examples of stopping times.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] While it is relatively straightforward to show that essentially all stopping times are hitting times, it can be much more difficult to show that a certain hitting time is a stopping time.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] The latter types of results are known as the Début theorem.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Stopping times are frequently used to generalize certain properties of stochastic processes to situations in which the required property is satisfied in only a local sense.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] First, if *X* is a process and τ is a stopping time, then *X**τ* is used to denote the process *X* stopped at time *τ*.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Stopping times, with time index set *I* = [0,∞), are often divided into one of several types depending on whether it is possible to predict when they are about to occur.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] A stopping time *τ* is **predictable** if it is equal to the limit of an increasing sequence of stopping times *τ**n* satisfying *τ**n* < *τ* whenever *τ* > 0.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] The sequence *τ**n* is said to *announce* *τ*, and predictable stopping times are sometimes known as *announceable*.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Examples of predictable stopping times are hitting times of continuous and adapted processes.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] If *τ* is the first time at which a continuous and real valued process *X* is equal to some value *a*, then it is announced by the sequence *τ**n*, where *τ**n* is the first time at which *X* is within a distance of 1/*n* of *a*.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] A stopping time *τ* is **totally inaccessible** if it can never be announced by an increasing sequence of stopping times.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Equivalently, P(*τ* = *σ* < ∞) = 0 for every predictable time *σ*.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Examples of totally inaccessible stopping times include the jump times of Poisson processes.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Every stopping time *τ* can be uniquely decomposed into an accessible and totally inaccessible time.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] That is, there exists a unique accessible stopping time σ and totally inaccessible time υ such that *τ* = *σ* whenever *σ* < ∞, *τ* = *υ* whenever *υ* < ∞, and *τ* = ∞ whenever *σ* = *υ* = ∞.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Note that in the statement of this decomposition result, stopping times do not have to be almost surely finite, and can equal ∞.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] Clinical trials in medicine often perform interim analysis, in order to determine whether the trial has already met its endpoints.
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] However, interim analysis create the risk of false-positive results, and therefore stopping boundaries are used to determine the number and timing of interim analysis (also known as alpha-spending, to denote the rate of false positives).
[src:martingale-theory/stopping-time] At each of R interim tests, the trial is stopped if the likelihood is below a threshold p, which depends on the method used.
